Task 1: Advanced Data Structures (25 marks)
Implement and compare the performance of different data structures for a route planning application
Implementation (15 marks):
• Implement a Binary Search Tree (BST) and an AVL Tree (self-balancing) to store city locations
with associated data (coordinates, population, distance).
1.
• Implement a Min-Heap for priority queue operations (e.g. next nearest city to visit). Implement
a Hash Table with open-addressing or chaining collision handling for fast city lookups.
Analysis (10 marks):
• Provide theoretical time complexity analysis (Big-O notation) for insertion, deletion, and search
for each structure. Acknowledge the constant factor hidden by Big-O and discuss its practical
significance.
• Conduct empirical testing with datasets of 100, 1,000, and 10,000 nodes. Measure actual wall-
clock time.
• Compare actual performance with theoretical predictions using labelled graphs and tables.
• Justify which data structure is most appropriate for each use case (frequent inserts vs frequent
lookups vs priority access).